# Policy Schema: Always Backward Compatible

`policy.json` is git-tracked and shared across every user of the repo. Users may be on
different daemon versions. **The schema must always be readable by any older daemon without
manual version tracking or manual migration steps.**

There is no version constant to bump. There is no `MAX_POLICY_VERSION`. Backward compatibility
is enforced by construction — by following these rules every time.

## Adding a field (the only allowed way to extend the schema)

Every new field on `Policy` in `src/policy.rs` **must** carry `#[serde(default)]`.

```rust
// ✅ CORRECT — older daemons that don't know this field get the default
#[serde(default)]
pub my_new_cap: Option<u64>,

// ❌ WRONG — older daemons will fail to deserialize the file
pub my_new_cap: u64,
```

Serde ignores unknown fields when deserializing, so a file written by a newer daemon is
always loadable by an older one.

## Removing or renaming a field (never allowed)

**Never remove or rename a field.** An older file still contains the old key; removing it
from the struct means the daemon silently ignores data the user set intentionally.

If a field is obsolete:
- Mark it with a `// DEPRECATED` comment
- Keep it in the struct with `#[serde(default)]`
- Stop reading it in logic, but keep deserializing it so old files remain valid

```rust
// ✅ CORRECT — keeps old files valid, stops using the value
/// DEPRECATED: replaced by `newCap`. Kept for backward-compatible deserialization.
#[serde(default)]
pub old_cap: Option<u64>,
```

## Changing a field's type or meaning (not allowed — add a new field instead)

If the semantics of an existing field need to change, add a **new field** alongside the old
one. The migration logic in `load_policy()` / `compile()` reads the old field and derives
the new field's value when the new one is absent.

```rust
// Old field stays, new field added with default
#[serde(default)]
pub lease: Option<Value>,          // original
#[serde(default)]
pub lease_v2: Option<LeaseConfig>, // new shape — derived from `lease` when absent
```

## All existing fields already comply

Every field on `Policy` already carries `#[serde(default)]` or `#[serde(default = "fn")]`.
Any new field must follow the same pattern — the linter/compiler will not catch a missing
default, so this rule is the enforcement.
